question8b.value:
a.	missing, erroneous, or overly consistent responses; 
Participants will not be excluded from the analyses based on missing data. If data of the fMRI task, PPQ, Auditory startling task or hormone collection is missing, data will be imputed by means of multiple imputation (MI) with the package ‘mice’ (Van Buuren &amp; Groothuis-Oudshoorn, 2011).

b.	failing check-tests or suspicion probes; 
-	Neuro-imaging data: when no significant difference is observed in neural response for the contrast threatening vs. neutral videos, data of participant will not be excluded from the analysis if we are certain that the task protocol was performed correctly (e.g. screen was working, instructions were provided correctly). 
-	Observed protective behavior: when the 80 dB sound is not presented in the video. Data of that specific participant is not coded for protective behavior. Data of the participant will be coded when no startle response is observed in the behavior of the participant during the sound exposure. 

c.	demographic exclusions; 
A priori stated exclusion criteria were as followed. Participants were not included in the study when they reported 1. not to live in the same house as their partner (and biological mother of the child); 2. to have an endocrine disorder; 3. alcohol and/or drug abuse; 4. the use of medication potentially interfering with the endocrine system; 5. MRI contraindications, including metallic foreign objects, neurological disorders, and claustrophobia; 6. having a psychiatric disorder; 7. having a cardiovascular disease; 8. not to speak Dutch fluently; 9. to have a upper torso injury; 10. already using a baby carrier more than five hours per week; 11. Participation in the VIPP-PRE study. Due to difficulties including participants, we decided to deviate from a priori stated exclusion in eight cases. 


d.	data-based outlier criteria; 
Possible data-based outliers will be detected based on visual inspection of the data. For the detected outliers, values lower than Q1-1.5*IQR or higher than Q3+1.5*IQR, notes on deviating data collection procedures will be checked in the logbooks. When it is noted that something went wrong or different during the data collection procedure, the outlier will be removed from the dataset. Specifically for salivary data, reported medication use and mouth health reported at the assessment date will be taken into account as well. If there is no reason to exclude the outlier, data will be Winsorized.
Preprocessed fMRI data will be checked for excessive head motion (&gt; 3.0 mm) and data with excessive head motion will be excluded. Sensitivity analyses for the second-level analyses will be performed excluding data with head motion between 1.4mm and 3.0 mm.


e.	method-based outlier criteria (e.g. too short or long response times).
Logbooks and videos will be checked to make sure that the research procedure was followed accurately When it is noted that the task is not performed following protocol, data will be removed from analyses.  Examples of method-based outliers are: saliva is not placed in the freezer/cooling back directly after collection, the sound of the AST is not played, participant and infant are not visible on the video tape.

